"Predictive Modeling for Heart Attack Risk Assessment using Machine Learning"¶

Introduction: Cardiovascular diseases (CVDs) are a leading cause of morbidity and mortality worldwide, imposing a significant burden on healthcare systems and economies. Early detection and accurate risk assessment are essential for effective prevention and management of CVDs. In recent years, predictive modeling techniques leveraging machine learning algorithms have emerged as promising tools for assessing an individual's risk of developing cardiovascular conditions, such as heart attacks. This study focuses on utilizing a comprehensive set of objective and subjective features to develop predictive models for heart attack risk assessment.

The dataset includes objective features such as age, height, weight, gender, systolic and diastolic blood pressure, as well as examination features like cholesterol and glucose levels. Additionally, subjective features such as smoking, alcohol intake, and physical activity are incorporated. These features provide a multifaceted view of an individual's health status and lifestyle factors that may influence cardiovascular health.

By harnessing the power of machine learning, we aim to develop accurate and interpretable predictive models that can effectively identify individuals at elevated risk of experiencing a heart attack. These models have the potential to assist healthcare professionals in early intervention and personalized preventative strategies, ultimately contributing to the reduction of CVD-related morbidity and mortality.

Features:¶

  • Age | Objective Feature | age | int (days)
  • Height | Objective Feature | height | int (cm) |
  • Weight | Objective Feature | weight | float (kg) |
  • Gender | Objective Feature | gender | categorical code |
  • Systolic blood pressure | Examination Feature | ap_hi | int |
  • Diastolic blood pressure | Examination Feature | ap_lo | int |
  • Cholesterol | Examination Feature | cholesterol | 1: normal, 2: above normal, 3: well above normal |
  • Glucose | Examination Feature | gluc | 1: normal, 2: above normal, 3: well above normal |
  • Smoking | Subjective Feature | smoke | binary | 0: Non-Smoker, 1: Smoker
  • Alcohol intake | Subjective Feature | alco | binary | 0: Non-alcoholic, 1: Alcoholic
  • Physical activity | Subjective Feature | active | binary | 0: Inactive, 1:Active
  • Presence or absence of cardiovascular disease | Target Variable | cardio | binary | 0: No Heart disease, 1: Heart disease

To enhance the predictive performance of our models, we've implemented outlier removal, specifically targeting instances falling outside the range of 2.5% to 97.5% for features including ap_hi, ap_lo, weight, and height. Also, the id column has been removed as it has no role in predicting the disease. Following this process, the dataset has been refined from 70,000 to 55,403 records.

In [27]:
### Outlier Removal
df.drop(df[(df['height'] > df['height'].quantile(0.975)) | (df['height'] < df['height'].quantile(0.025))].index,inplace=True)
df.drop(df[(df['weight'] > df['weight'].quantile(0.975)) | (df['weight'] < df['weight'].quantile(0.025))].index,inplace=True)
df.drop(df[(df['ap_hi'] > df['ap_hi'].quantile(0.975)) | (df['ap_hi'] < df['ap_hi'].quantile(0.025))].index,inplace=True)
df.drop(df[(df['ap_lo'] > df['ap_lo'].quantile(0.975)) | (df['ap_lo'] < df['ap_lo'].quantile(0.025))].index,inplace=True)

Model Evaluation¶

In [64]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, roc_auc_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report
def evaluate_model(predictions, model_name):
    print(f"Results for {model_name}:")
    print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_os, predictions))
    print("ROC-AUC:", roc_auc_score(y_os, predictions))
    print("Confusion Matrix:\n", confusion_matrix(y_os, predictions))
    print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_os, predictions))
    print("-" * 50)

Key Findings¶

Top Contributing Features:

  • Weight (0.24): The most important feature, suggesting that weight is the strongest predictor in your model.
  • Height (0.21): The second most important feature, indicating a significant contribution to the models predictions.
  • Age (0.18): Also highly important, showing that age is a key factor in the predictions

Moderately Important Features:

  • ap_hi (0.17): Systolic blood pressure has a notable influence on the model, making it an important predictor.
  • ap_lo (0.09): Diastolic blood pressure has a moderate impact on the models performance.

Less Important Features:

  • Cholesterol (0.04): This feature contributes less compared to the top predictors but still has some impact.
  • Gender (0.02) and Gluc (0.02): These features have minimal influence on the model.
  • Smoke (0.01), Alco (0.01), and Active (0.01): These features are the least important in the model, indicating that their influence on the predictions is very small.

Interpretation

Health Metrics: Variables such as weight, height, age, and blood pressure (ap_hi and ap_lo) are significant predictors in the Random Forest model. These findings align with common medical knowledge, where these metrics are critical indicators of various health conditions.

Lifestyle Factors: Features like smoking status (smoke), alcohol consumption (alco), and physical activity (active) are less influential in this model. This could be due to a variety of reasons, such as lower variability in the dataset for these factors or their lesser direct impact on the outcome being predicted.

Medical Metrics: Cholesterol and glucose levels (gluc) have some influence but are not as critical as the top features. This might suggest that while these metrics are relevant, they are not the primary drivers of the models predictions.

Conclusion The Random Forest model has identified that weight, height, and age are the most influential features in predicting the outcome. Blood pressure readings also play a significant role, while lifestyle factors like smoking and alcohol consumption have minimal impact. These insights can help focus on the most critical features for predictive modeling and potentially guide further data collection or feature engineering efforts.
